@page "/face/intro"

    <div class="content">
        <h2>Azure Face API</h2>

        <p>
            <img src="images/Face/face.detection.jpg" class="img-responsive" width="420" alt="Face Detection example by Microsoft" />
        </p>

        <p>
            Azure Face API is used to detect, recognize and analyze human faces in images.<br />
            All interaction with API is done via REST APIs.<br />

            If you already have Azure Face API setup, <a href="face/v1.0/persongroups">start exploring</a>!
        </p>

        <h3>Get started</h3>

        <p>
            To get started go to <a href="https://portal.azure.com/">Microsoft Azure Portal</a> or try it for free at <a href="https://azure.microsoft.com/en-au/services/cognitive-services/face/">Try it for free</a>, create Face API and copy the URL as well as the subscription key.<br />
            Alternatively, you can also use Azure CLI to create the resource in PowerShell:
        </p>

        <p>
            <pre><code>az cognitiveservices account create --kind Face --location EastUS --name face-api-name --resource-group PoC --sku F0 --yes
az cognitiveservices account keys list --name face-api-name --resource-group resource-group-name
</code></pre>
        </p>

        <p>
            <ol>
                <li>Copy <b>"endpoint"</b> value from first command (e.g. <i>https://eastus.api.cognitive.microsoft.com</i> or <i>https://sswsophieface-dev.cognitiveservices.azure.com</i>).</li>
                <li>Copy <b>"key1"</b> from second command.</li>
                <li>That's all! <a href="face/v1.0/persongroups">Start exploring</a>!</li>
            </ol>

            <a href="images/Face/azure-cli-create-face-api.png" target="_blank"><img src="images/Face/azure-cli-create-face-api.png" alt="Azure CLI creating Azure Face API" style="max-width: 600px;" /></a>
        </p>

