        <h3>Check for usage</h3>

        <p>When using Azure Face API, it's a goo idea to check consumption of your APIs, especially if the usage can't be directly controlled.<br/></p>

        <h4 class="pt-2">Free tier (F0)</h4>
        <div>
            <p>You have 2 options for free tier.</p>

            <h5>Azure Portal</h5>

            <ol>
                <li>Go to Azure Portal</li>
                <li>Find your Azure Face API</li>
                <li>Go to overview</li>
            </ol>

            <a href="images/Face/azure-portal-face-api-usage-free-tier.png" target="_blank"><img src="images/Face/azure-portal-face-api-usage-free-tier.png" alt="Azure CLI - get usage for Face API free tier" style="max-width: 600px;" /></a>

            <h5>Azure CLI</h5>

            <p>In PowerShell use the following command:</p>

            <pre><code>az cognitiveservices account list-usage --name face-api-name --resource-group resource-group-name</code></pre>

            <a href="images/Face/azure-cli-face-api-usage-free-tier.png" target="_blank"><img src="images/Face/azure-cli-face-api-usage-free-tier.png" alt="Azure Portal - get usage for Face API free tier" style="max-width: 600px;" /></a>
        </div>

        <h4 class="pt-2">Paid tier</h4>

        <div>
            <p>Currently, the easiest to checks usage on paid tier is to go to Azure Portal cost analysis.</p>

            <p>In Azure Portal:</p>
            <ol>
                <li>Go to the resource group of Azure Face API</li>
                <li>Cost analysis</li>
                <li>Click your resource under resources</li>
            </ol>

            <a href="images/Face/azure-portal-face-api-usage-paid-tier.png" target="_blank"><img src="images/Face/azure-portal-face-api-usage-paid-tier.png" alt="Azure portal - get usage for Face API paid tier" style="max-width: 600px;" /></a>
        </div>

